<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="factoring-leading-coefficient-1">
  <title>Factoring Trinomials with Leading Coefficients of 1</title>

  <p>
    Factoring a trinomial of form <m>x^2+bx+c</m>, where <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are integers, is essentially the reversal of a FOIL process.  For this reason, we can develop a strategy by investigating a FOIL expansion.  Let's expand <m>(x+4)(x+6)</m>.   
    <md>
      <mrow>(x+4)(x+6)\amp=x^2+6x+4x+24</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=x^2+10x+24</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>
    Let's observe that the linear coefficient, <m>10</m>, is the sum of <m>4</m> and <m>6</m> whereas the constant term, <m>24</m>, is the product of <m>4</m> and <m>6</m>.  Since we expanded <m>(x+4)(x+6)</m>, we can infer that finding the constants in a factorization of trinomials of form <m>x^2+bx+c</m> is dependent upon determining two numbers that sum to <m>b</m> and multiply to <m>c</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    From the factor pairs and sums shown in <xref ref="factoring-trinomial-lc1-table-1">Table</xref>, we can infer the following factorizations. 
  </p>
  <sidebyside widths="48% 48%" margins="0%">

    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x^2+7x+6\amp=(x+1)(x+6)</mrow>
        <mrow>x^2+5x+6\amp=(x+2)(x+3)</mrow>
        <mrow>x^2-7x+6\amp=(x-1)(x-6)</mrow>
        <mrow>x^2-5x+6\amp=(x-2)(x-3)</mrow>
      </md> 
    </p>

    <table xml:id="factoring-trinomial-lc1-table-1">
      <caption>Factor pairs of <m>6</m></caption>
      <tabular>
        <col halign="center" />
        <col halign="center"/>
        <row bottom="medium">
          <cell>
            <line>factors</line>
          </cell>
          <cell>
            <line>sum</line>
          </cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>1,6</m></cell>
          <cell><m>7</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>2,3</m></cell>
          <cell><m>5</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>-1,-6</m></cell>
          <cell><m>-7</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>-2,-3</m></cell>
          <cell><m>-5</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>

  </sidebyside> 
  <p>
    Just as noteworthy, since the factor pairs shown in <xref ref="factoring-trinomial-lc1-table-1">Table</xref> form an exhaustive list, we cannot factor any trinomial of form <m>x^2+bx+6</m> where b is not one of the four numbers shown in the sum column.  Such trinomials are said to be prime.  For example, <m>x^2+3x+6</m> is prime.
  </p>

  <example xml:is="factoring-trinomial-lc1-ex-1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Factor <m>x^2-8x+15</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Our first task is to determine a factor pair that multiplies to <m>15</m> and adds to <m>-8</m>.  Since the product is positive and the sum is negative, we are searching for two negative numbers.  The pair that works is <m>-3</m> and <m>-5</m>.  This gives us:
          <me>x^2-8x+15=(x-3)(x-5)</me>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:is="factoring-trinomial-lc1-ex-1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Factor <m>w^2-4w-12</m>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since our factor pair needs to multiply to a negative value <m>(-12)</m>, one the numbers in the pair must be positive and the other negative.  Let's note that <m>6</m> and <m>2</m> multiply to 12 and have a difference of <m>4</m>.  This can be helpful in determining that the factor pair that multiplies to <m>-12</m> and adds to <m>-4</m> is <m>-6</m> and <m>2</m>.  This gives us:
        <me>w^2-4w-12=(w-6)(w+2)</me>. 
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
